the wrriteup:

We began by testing the core hypothesis behind The 90% Trap using historical Kalshi political prediction market data (2021–Dec 2025, volume > 1000), constructing a calibration curve by bucketing markets based on final traded prices as proxy probabilities and comparing them against actual resolution frequencies. The initial results showed strong apparent calibration at extreme probabilities (0–10% and 90–100%), but a striking breakdown in the mid-range (30–80%), where observed outcomes became highly unstable and inconsistent across buckets.

However, deeper inspection revealed that this “broken middle” is likely not a simple calibration failure but a structural artifact of the dataset: political markets are highly heterogeneous, mixing fundamentally different types of prediction problems (electoral outcomes, policy/institutional events, and high-entropy one-off event markets). This likely causes the mid-range probabilities to reflect heterogeneous uncertainty regimes rather than a single unified forecasting system.

As a result, the initial calibration curve cannot yet be interpreted as a single global efficiency measure. Instead, it reflects an aggregation of multiple market dynamics with different entropy structures and convergence behaviors.

---
Next Step in the Analysis

To correctly test whether prediction markets are truly “overconfident at extreme probabilities,” the next step is to decompose the dataset into meaningful market categories (by structure/entropy type) and recompute calibration curves within each segment. This will allow us to determine whether:

Extreme probability accuracy is consistent across all political market types, or
It is driven primarily by low-entropy (high-certainty) markets such as elections, while high-entropy event markets distort mid-range calibration.

Only after this segmentation can we isolate whether the observed pattern reflects true miscalibration behavior or a mixture-induced artifact in the aggregated curve

