Current Analysis Summary

After building the initial calibration curve, we observed what appeared to be severe miscalibration in the middle probability ranges. To investigate whether this was a genuine prediction market failure or a consequence of mixing fundamentally different market types, we segmented political markets into three categories: Electoral (A), Policy (B), and Event/High-Entropy (C).

The segmentation revealed that the apparent calibration breakdown largely disappeared. Instead, we found that most political markets finish at extreme probabilities (0–10% or 90–100%), with very few markets resolving from the middle probability ranges. Markets reaching extreme probabilities were extraordinarily accurate across all three categories.

Our next step is to quantify this behavior more rigorously by measuring calibration error (observed resolution frequency minus expected probability) and examining the distribution of final probabilities. This will allow us to determine whether markets are actually overconfident, underconfident, or well-calibrated at extreme probability levels, and whether the apparent "broken middle" is primarily a sample-size phenomenon.


Calibration Error by Bucket — Introduction & Methodology

To move beyond visual inspection of calibration curves, we now compute calibration error by probability bucket. This directly quantifies how far prediction markets deviate from perfect calibration at each confidence level.

Instead of only comparing predicted vs observed frequencies qualitatively, we measure the numerical gap between them across discrete probability ranges.

Methodology
Bucket predicted probabilities
Use existing bins (0–10, 10–20, …, 90–100)
Treat each bucket midpoint as the expected probability
(e.g., 80–90 → 85%)
Compute observed frequency per bucket

Already derived:

actual resolution frequency=
total markets
YES outcomes
	​


Calculate calibration error
For each bucket:

Calibration Error=Observed Frequency−Expected Probability
Interpretation
Positive error → underconfidence (outcomes happen more than priced in)
Negative error → overconfidence (outcomes happen less than priced in)
Near zero → well-calibrated
Why this matters

This transforms the analysis from a shape-based curve interpretation into a precise bias measurement, allowing us to answer:

Are extreme probabilities systematically miscalibrated?
Is the “90% trap” actually real or just visual distortion?
Which probability regions (if any) show consistent directional bias?

This becomes the quantitative backbone for validating or rejecting the original

